POWER STRUCTURE
--------------------------------------------------

Influence inside the country is distributed among:

• Government Leadership
• Bureaucratic Institutions
• Economic Elites
• Security Establishment
• Civil Society

Policies shift the balance of influence.

Severe imbalance increases long-term instability.

--------------------------------------------------
GLOBAL ACTOR SYSTEM
--------------------------------------------------

Instead of individual countries, the world consists of six evolving blocs:

1. Western Democracies
2. Rising Industrial Powers
3. Resource Exporting States
4. Developing Populations
5. Tech-Dominant Economies
6. Fragile Regions

These blocs react strategically to player actions.

Global relationships evolve over time.

--------------------------------------------------
GLOBAL CYCLES
--------------------------------------------------

Every 8–12 turns global conditions may shift:

• economic boom
• global recession
• technological breakthrough era
• geopolitical rivalry period
• environmental stress period

These cycles influence all countries.

--------------------------------------------------
EVENT SYSTEM
--------------------------------------------------

Each turn there is a 15% chance of an event.

Event categories:

• Economic
• Political
• Technological
• Environmental
• Diplomatic

Events should influence systems but not dominate gameplay.

--------------------------------------------------
SYSTEM FEEDBACK LOOPS
--------------------------------------------------

System dynamics reinforce themselves.

Examples:

High Public Trust →
greater reform success

Low Public Trust →
policy resistance

Rapid growth →
higher complexity risk

Extreme control →
lower innovation

Suppressed dissent →
hidden instability grows

--------------------------------------------------
SYSTEM ENTROPY
--------------------------------------------------

Over time all systems accumulate stress.

Without reform:

• corruption pressure rises
• infrastructure ages
• institutional efficiency declines

Governance requires constant adaptation.

--------------------------------------------------
NATIONAL REPUTATION
--------------------------------------------------

Global actors gradually develop perceptions of the country.

Possible reputations:

• reliable
• opportunistic
• aggressive
• unstable
• visionary

Reputation evolves slowly and affects diplomacy and trade.

--------------------------------------------------
PLAYER STRATEGY DETECTION
--------------------------------------------------

Track the player's governing style over time:

• stability focused
• economic expansion focused
• reform oriented
• authoritarian control
• diplomacy oriented

The simulation adapts to repeated strategies.

